page.text: Cardno has been retained by the City of Oldsmar to prepare a traffic study to evaluate
intersection improvement options at the intersection of Tampa Road (SR 584) and Bay Arbor
Boulevard in Oldsmar, Florida. The intersection location is depicted in Figure 1. The study was
requested by the City of Oldsmar to address the concerns raised by the City Council at the City
Council meeting held on Tuesday, April 1, 2014. This traffic technical memorandum presents
the results of the traffic study. The elements of the traffic technical memorandum include the
• Review of daily and PM peak hour volumes at the intersection of Tampa Road
(SR 584) and Bay Arbor Boulevard from the original Transportation Analysis
(July 2006) and the Traffic Analysis Update Study (February 2014)
• Traffic signal warrant analysis at the intersection of Tampa Road (SR 584) and
• Evaluation of intersection improvements at the intersection of Tampa Road and
The study was prepared in accordance with methodology discussions with the City of Oldsmar
staff. The purpose of the traffic study is to document the existing traffic conditions, to assess the
existing traffic volumes in comparison with 2005 traffic volumes, to determine if a signal is
warranted at the intersection of Tampa Road and Bay Arbor Boulevard and to evaluate the
impacts of an alternative intersection configuration at the intersection of Tampa Road and Bay
Arbor Boulevard. The data, analysis and findings are summarized in this traffic study.

page.text: Turning movement counts (TMC), by 15-minute periods, were conducted at the intersections of

In addition to the turning movement counts, pedestrian and bicycle activity were collected at
each of the study intersections. The pedestrian and bicycle counts are included in Appendix B.

text.b: Tampa Road (SR 584) and Bay Arbor Boulevard

page.text: As requested, an assessment of the 2005 and the 2014 traffic volumes from the original
Transportation Analysis (July 2006) and the Traffic Analysis Update Study (February 2014) was
conducted. The assessment revealed the following:
The 2014 daily approach volumes are less than the 2005 daily approach volumes, with the
exception of the southbound approach that increased from 1,100 to 1,300. The eastbound and
westbound through volumes during the PM peak hour increased significantly in the eastbound
direction. The eastbound through volume grew approximately 4.7 percent annually with an
overall increase of 40 percent in 8.5 years. The westbound through volume grew approximately
1.8 percent annually with an overall increase of 15 percent in 8.5 years. Therefore, although the
daily volumes decreased, during the PM peak hour the volumes along Tampa Road have
increased. The southbound approach volumes at the intersection of Tampa Road and Bay Arbor
Boulevard have increased with the construction of the Bay Arbor Place development. A
comparison of the traffic volumes are shown in Figure 4.
The 2014 AM, midday and PM peak hour, peak-season adjusted existing volumes for each count
day (Tuesday through Thursday) are shown in Figures 5 through 7. Detailed intersection
analyses were performed for the AM, midday, and PM peak hour for each of the three days. The
intersection analyses were performed for the intersection of Tampa Road at Bay Arbor
Boulevard and at Shady Oaks Drive. The intersection analyses for the intersections were
performed using Synchro, utilizing the Highway Capacity Manual (HCM) methodologies for
unsignalized and signalized intersections. The existing local signal timings for the intersection
of Tampa Road and Shady Oaks Drive were supplied by Pinellas County and used in the
analysis. The existing timings are included in Appendix B.

i.b: Warrant 1 – Eight-Hour Vehicular Volume

text.i: Support:
The Minimum Vehicular Volume, Condition A, is intended for application at locations where a
large volume of intersecting traffic is the principal reason to consider installing a traffic control
signal.
The Interruption of Continuous Traffic, Condition B, is intended for application at locations
where Condition A is not satisfied and where the traffic volume on a major street is so heavy that
traffic on a minor intersecting street suffers excessive delay or conflict in entering or crossing
the major street.
It is intended that Warrant 1 be treated as a single warrant. If Condition A is satisfied, then
Warrant 1 is satisfied and analyses of Condition B is not needed.

i.b: Standard:
The need for a traffic control signal shall be considered if an engineering study finds that one
of the following conditions exist for each of any 8 hours of an average day:
A. The vehicles per hour given in both of the 100 percent columns of Condition A in
Table 4C-1 exist on the major-street and the higher-volume minor-street approaches,
respectively, to the intersection; or
B. The vehicles per hour given in both of the 100 percent columns of Condition B in
Table 4C-1 exist on the major-street and the higher-volume minor-street approaches,
respectively, to the intersection.
In applying each condition the major-street and minor-street volumes shall be for the same 8
hours. On the minor street, the higher volume shall not be required to be on the same
approach during each of these 8 hours.

i.b: Warrant 7 – Crash Experience

text.i: The Crash Experience signal warrant conditions are intended for application where the severity
and frequency of crashes are the principal reasons to consider installing a traffic control signal.

i.b: Standard:
The need for a traffic control signal shall be considered if an engineering study finds that all
of the following criteria are met:
A. Adequate trial of alternatives with satisfactory observance and enforcement has
failed to reduce the crash frequency; and
B. Five or more reported crashes, of types susceptible to correction by a traffic control
signal, have occurred within a 12-month period, each crash involving personal injury or
property damage apparently exceeding the applicable requirements for a reportable crash; and
C. For each of any 8 hours of an average day, the vehicles per hour (vph) given in both
of the 80 percent columns of Condition A in Table 4C-1 (see Section 4C.02), or the vph in both
of the 80 percent columns of Condition B in Table 4C-1 exists on the major-street and the
higher-volume minor-street approach, respectively, to the intersection, or the volume of
pedestrian traffic is not less than 80 percent of the requirements specified in the Pedestrian
Volume warrant. These major-street and minor-street volumes shall be for the same 8 hours.
On the minor street, the higher volume shall not be required to be on the same approach
during each of the 8 hours.

page.text: As part of this traffic study, intersection improvements were evaluated for the intersection of
Tampa Road and Bay Arbor Boulevard. The alternative intersection configuration was based on
modifications suggested by the City Council at the City Council meeting on Tuesday, April 1,
2014. The alternative intersection configuration includes modifying the intersection to a bi-
directional median opening; removing the southbound and northbound through and left-turn
movements and permitting the east-west left-turn movements. With the modifications, the
southbound through and left-turning vehicles (on Bay Arbor Boulevard) will have to make a
right turn and then a westbound U-turn at the intersection of Tampa Road and Shady Oaks Drive
in order to travel eastbound on Tampa Road. Currently, there are vehicles making this
movement to avoid crossing Tampa Road at the intersection. In addition, the northbound
through and left-turning vehicles (on Emerald Bay Drive) will have to make a right and then an
eastbound U-turn at the next bi-directional median opening (Bay Arbor Place east driveway).
The diverted volumes are shown in Figures 9 through 11.

page.text: The study was requested by the City of Oldsmar to address the concerns raised by the City

memorandum presents the results of the traffic study. The elements of the traffic technical
memorandum include a review of the daily and PM peak hour volumes from previous and
current traffic volume data, a traffic signal warrant analysis at the intersection of Tampa Road
(SR 584) and Bay Arbor Boulevard and an evaluation of intersection improvements at Tampa
Based on an assessment of 2005 and 2014 traffic volume data, the 2014 daily approach volumes
are less than the 2005 daily approach volumes, with the exception of the southbound approach
that increased from 1,100 to 1,300. However, the eastbound and westbound through volumes
during the PM peak hour increased from 2005 to 2014. Therefore, although the daily volumes
have decreased, the volumes along Tampa Road during the PM peak hour have increased. As
expected, the southbound approach volumes at the intersection of Tampa Road and Bay Arbor
Boulevard have increased with the construction of the Bay Arbor Place development.
A signal warrant analysis was performed for the intersection of Tampa Road and Bay Arbor
Boulevard using the traffic volume, crash data and other pertinent information. The analysis
examined two applicable warrants for this intersection, Warrants 1 and 7, as defined by the
Manual of Uniform Traffic Control Devices (MUTCD, FHWA, 2009 Edition and the Manual on
Uniform Traffic Studies (MUTS), FDOT, April 2003. Based on the analysis, none of the
Warrants are satisfied and a traffic signal is not recommended. Due to the incidence of angle
crashes at this intersection, five crashes during a 12-month period, more restrictive control was
The more restrictive control for reducing angle crashes is modifying the intersection to a bi-
directional median opening which will restrict the southbound and northbound through and left-

page.text: turn movements. Based on the analysis, the northbound and southbound approach LOS at the

The modifications to the intersection of Tampa Road and Bay Arbor Boulevard will affect the
adjacent intersection of Shady Oaks Drive to the west and the Bay Arbor Place east driveway.

U-turn movement, reducing delay and the expected queue.
Finally, a turn lane length assessment was performed for the westbound left-turn lane at the
intersection of Tampa Road and Shady Oaks Drive and the eastbound left-turn lane at the bi-
